'''Jūnichoku''' (十二直) is one of the {{ill|Calendrical Notes|lt=calendar annotations|ja|暦注}}, comprising twelve categories: '''Ken, Jo, Mitsu, Taira, Sadamu, Toru, Yaburu, Ayabu, Naru, Osamu, Hiraku, and Tozuru'''. These are often recorded in the middle section of calendars, leading to the alternative name "Middle Section" (中段) or "Middle Section Twelve Categories" (中段十二直). They are frequently used alongside systems like the {{ill|Twenty-Seven Lunar Mansions|ja|二十七宿}} or {{ill|Twenty-Eight Lunar Mansions|ja|二十八宿}}.
== Overview ==
The {{ill|Big Dipper|ja|北斗七星}} has been regarded with reverence since ancient times, and the motion of this constellation was aligned with the {{ill|Chinese Zodiac|ja|十二支}} to determine auspicious and inauspicious days, forming the basis of Jūnichoku.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|和書|title=暦Wiki/十二直 - 国立天文台暦計算室 |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220827083341/https://eco.mtk.nao.ac.jp/koyomi/wiki/BDBDC6F3C4BE.html |website=web.archive.org |date=2022-08-27 |access-date=2023-01-14}}</ref> Until the early {{ill|Shōwa period|ja|昭和時代}}, Jūnichoku was the most emphasized system among calendar annotations. However, more recently, systems like {{ill|Rokuyō|ja|六曜}} and {{ill|Nine Celestial Stems|ja|九星}} have gained prominence, and Jūnichoku is now less frequently used.<ref>[http://homepage1.nifty.com/gyouseinet/calendar/12tyoku.htm About Jūnichoku]</ref> It is also rarely included in {{ill|seven-day calendars|ja|七曜表}}.
The handle of the Big Dipper (斗柄) is believed to rotate around the {{ill|North Star|ja|北極星}}, and its alignment with the directions of the twelve zodiac animals is used to determine Jūnichoku assignments. The system employs {{ill|Solar Terms|ja|節月}} to allocate categories. For each solar month, the day when the zodiac of the evening Dipper aligns with the day's zodiac is designated as "Ken." In practice, the first day of the solar month repeats the previous day’s [[Category:Pages with redlinks to fill]][[Category:ZZZZZZZZZ Unlinked]] [[Category:defautsort]] {{DEFAULTSORT:Twelve Directions}}[[category:unsorted completion categories]] [[Category:ZZZZZZZZZ Unlinked]] [[Category:defautsort]] {{DEFAULTSORT:Twelve Directions}}[[category:unsorted completion categories]] [[Category:ZZZZZZZZZ Unlinked]] [[Category:defautsort]] {{DEFAULTSORT:Twelve Directions}}[[category:unsorted completion categories]] {{DEFAULTSORT::Twelve Directions}}[[Category:ZZZZZZZZZ Unlinked]] [[Category:defautsort]] {{DEFAULTSORT:Twelve Directions}}[[category:unsorted completion categories]] {{DEFAULTSORT::Twelve Directions}}[[Category:ZZZZZZZZZ Unlinked]] [[Category:defautsort]] {{DEFAULTSORT:Twelve Directions}}[[category:unsorted completion categories]] {{DEFAULTSORT::Twelve Directions}}[[Category:ZZZZZZZZZ Unlinked]] [[Category:defautsort]] {{DEFAULTSORT:Twelve Directions}}[[category:unsorted completion categories]] [[Category:ZZZZZZZZZ Unlinked]] [[Category:defautsort]] {{DEFAULTSORT:Twelve Directions}}[[category:unsorted completion categories]] {{DEFAULTSORT::Twelve Directions}}Category. For example, during the winter solstice, when the Dipper points north (Rat), the solar month is referred to as the "Ken-Zi Month."
However, contradictions arise when comparing Jūnichoku with systems like {{ill|Four Pillars of Destiny|ja|四柱推命}}, where certain zodiac combinations considered completely inauspicious in Four Pillars are treated as mixed or even auspicious in Jūnichoku. For instance, combinations like "Dragon-Dragon" or "Rooster-Rooster" are considered self-punishments ("Jikei") in Four Pillars but are categorized as "Ken" in Jūnichoku, carrying favorable elements.
