The [[:en:Big Dipper|Big Dipper]] has been regarded with reverence since ancient times, and the motion of this constellation was aligned with the [[:en:Earthly Branches|Chinese Zodiac]] to determine auspicious and inauspicious days, forming the basis of Jūnichoku.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|和書|title=暦Wiki/十二直 - 国立天文台暦計算室 |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220827083341/https://eco.mtk.nao.ac.jp/koyomi/wiki/BDBDC6F3C4BE.html |website=web.archive.org |date=2022-08-27 |access-date=2023-01-14}}</ref> Until the early {{ill|Shōwa period|ja|昭和時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shōwa period|qq=}}, Jūnichoku was the most emphasized system among calendar annotations. However, more recently, systems like {{ill|Rokuyō|ja|六曜|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Rokuyō|qq=}} and {{ill|Nine Stars|ja|九星|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nine Stars|qq=}} have gained prominence, and Jūnichoku is now less frequently used.<ref>[http://homepage1.nifty.com/gyouseinet/calendar/12tyoku.htm About Jūnichoku]</ref> It is also rarely included in {{ill|seven-day calendars|ja|七曜表|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/seven-day calendars|qq=}}.
